Curtain raiser.
"Please, I beg of you!" Queen Elvira implored, "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The Ice King sat on his throne, gazing down at his wife, with royal advisors standing beside him. The queen had given birth to a daughter. At the mere thought of this, the Ice King's brow furrowed in distaste.
The infant girl looked very much like her mother: pale blue eyes, snow-white hair, and a few strands of blue hair woven in. The Ice King thought that having a daughter would make him appear weak. After all, before this, he had only sons.
"You have only two options: kill this child or abandon her in the wilderness. Elvira, this is your punishment." He spat out her name with venom, as if it were poison. He always did.
The Ice Kingdom was not always a unified realm. It was once divided, with the northern lands comprising a non-magical kingdom, and the southern lands a kingdom teeming with magical powers. The endless wars between the two kingdoms were sparked by the north's avarice, until the south proposed a ceasefire.
At that time, the southern lands were desperate, and members of the royal family were willing to pay any price to prevent this bloody conflict. They proposed that the only princess be married to the north, become the queen of the north, and give birth to a son as the future king. Afterwards, the south would merge with the north, establishing a unified kingdom. The north accepted this proposal, and Princess Elvira thus married Prince Arcturus.
"Please, my king, for the sake of my child's safety, you can do anything to me – imprison me, exile me, or even kill me."
The Ice King looked down at the queen with disgust in his eyes. Perhaps, just perhaps, he would have a shred of pity for her. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, cared for him in his darkest moments, and borne him children.
"Alright. The child can live in the palace." Hearing the Ice King's words, the queen relaxed. "But," he added, "you will be put to death."
The queen bowed low, her face pale with fear.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter to an empty room in Elvira's quarters. After completing the task, he ordered the guards to bring Elvira to the public execution square.
When the guards escorted her to the execution grounds, the citizens saw their only queen – and the kindest queen – about to be put to death and were filled with outrage. Some people wept, others shouted and tried to attack the guards, while others wondered why this had to happen; but they all shared the same question.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they treating her like this?"
When Elvira drew near the wooden stake, the most feared man in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner for burning at the stake. The former queen, Elvira, was to be burned alive. No one should be sentenced to death by fire, not even a criminal. In the Ice Kingdom, burning at the stake was the cruelest punishment.
Elvira was bound to the wooden stake, and the king began to recount how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of the Ice Kingdom refused to believe, and would never accept the king's words. Then, the executioner lit the stake, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Elvira, live on!"
The grand hall fell silent.
In the southern wing of this cold palace, an endless ticking sound emanated from the room on the far left, where the former servants would often wonder what lay within, yet dared not approach out of fear. In the grand hall, the maids busied themselves, whispering amongst themselves and spreading rumors, some speculating that the Ice King's late wife, Queen Elvira, was imprisoned in this very room, waiting to be released.
They are entirely mistaken. Queen Elvira thought to herself as she walked towards the southern wing, the servants pacing along the wall, whispering amongst themselves, none of them knowing what lay within.
Of course, there are many rumors about her, as she is the only one permitted to enter the room.
She knocked on the door. "Miss Carly, are you inside?" Queen Elvira whispered softly, addressing the intricately decorated door, adorned with snowflakes and crown motifs, symbols of the royal family.
She wasn't sure if she would let him in this time, unlike before. I still have the bruises from the last time, Queen Elvira remembered the incident, and couldn't help but chuckle. It was when Carly had thrown a book at him, but as soon as she realized who it was, she apologized.
A faint noise echoed from within the room, as if it were saying she wouldn't be going anywhere, just staying there.
"May I come in?" Queen Elvira asked, still remembering the consequences of his uninvited entry last time.
A faint noise echoed from within the room, as if it were urging her to come in. Queen Elvira felt a chill, unsure if it was from the cold or the sound itself. Despite the Ice King having been there for many years, Queen Elvira still found it slightly odd to hear the sound coming from within.
"I've come in," Queen Elvira said, slowly opening the door. The scene within was, by normal standards, quite extraordinary, but also entirely expected. The room was cluttered with paper, books lay scattered everywhere, and the table was broken, with numerous ice sculptures scattered about. There were no windows, and hardly any light. The room was colder than any other part of the palace (which told its own story), and it looked as though it had been hit by a blizzard, with everything in disarray.
The girl in the room was huddled under a blanket on the bed, reading a notebook. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"What notebook are you reading?"
